[Our thanks to Roland Hübner for sharing this excellent article. It is nice when one's gut feelings are shared by others who have the analytic powers to test it. I have been uncomfortable with the heavy reliance on the R0 from early on, as the other cousins in the coronavirus family (SARS-CoV-1 and MERS-CoV) were also observed to have super-spreading events which were responsible for the majority of cases. The article above does an excellent job of walking one through the logic of the "cluster busting" strategy, doing backward tracing of infected individuals to identify who transmitted it to them and thereby had a high likelihood of having infected many others in a super-spreading event. South Korea seems to be a model country employing this strategy with apparent success, having periodic flare-ups lasting several weeks, identifying all of the clusters, and increased case finding. Can we learn from these successes or will we remain frozen in one way of looking at the outbreaks? - Mod.MPP]

